name: Reduced contrast sensitivity

Contrast sensitivity refers to a measure of how much contrast a person requires to see a target. Contrast-sensitivity measurements differ from acuity measurements; acuity is a measure of the spatial-resolving ability of the visual system under conditions of very high contrast, whereas contrast sensitivity is a measure of the threshold contrast for seeing a target.

name: Congenital nystagmus
description: Nystagmus dating from or present at birth.

name: Basal ganglia gliosis
description: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the basal ganglia.

name: Distal peripheral sensory neuropathy
description: Peripheral sensory neuropathy affecting primarily distal sensation.

name: Fluctuations in consciousness
description: Changes in one's level of awareness and responsiveness to their environment.

name: Progressive gait ataxia
description: A type of gait ataxia displaying progression of clinical severity.

name: Abnormal pyramidal sign
description: Functional neurological abnormalities related to dysfunction of the pyramidal tract.

name: Bipolar affective disorder
description: Bipolar disorder is an illness of mood characterized by alternating episodes of elevated and depressed moods, which are interspersed with euthymic periods.

name: Lower limb muscle weakness
description: Weakness of the muscles of the legs.

name: Focal-onset seizure
description: A focal-onset seizure is a type of seizure originating within networks limited to one hemisphere. They may be discretely localized or more widely distributed, and may originate in subcortical structures.

name: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the central nervous system
description: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the central nervous system

name: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the cerebrum
description: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebrum, also known as the telencephalon, the largest and most highly developed part of the human brain.

name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the corpus callosum
description: Absence or underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.

name: Type II diabetes mellitus
description: A type of diabetes mellitus initially characterized by insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia and subsequently by glucose interolerance and hyperglycemia.

name: Abnormal left ventricular function
description: Inability of the left ventricle to perform its normal physiologic function. Failure is either due to an inability to contract the left ventricle or the inability to relax completely and fill with blood during diastole.

name: Concentric hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
description: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with an symmetrical and concentric pattern of hypertrophy.

name: Abnormal anterior eye segment morphology
description: An abnormality of the anterior segment of the eyeball (which comprises the structures in front of the vitreous humor: the cornea, iris, ciliary body, and lens).

name: Abnormality of bone mineral density
description: This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone. Changes may affect all bones of the organism, just certain bones or only parts of bones and include decreased mineralisation as may be seen in osteoporosis or increased mineralisation and or ossification as in osteopetrosis, exostoses or any kind of atopic calicfications of different origin and distribution. The overall amount of mineralization of the bone-organ can be measured as the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones, usually measured by densitometry of the lumbar spine or hip. The measurements are usually reported as g/cm3 or as a Z-score (the number of standard deviations above or below the mean for the patient's age and sex). Note that measurement with this method does not reflect local changes in other bones, and as such might not be correct with regard the hole bone-organ.

name: Reduced bone mineral density
description: A reduction of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones.

name: Abnormal circulating carboxylic acid concentration
description: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carboxylic acid in the blood circulation.

name: Abnormality of acid-base homeostasis
description: An abnormality of the balance or maintenance of the balance of acids and bases in bodily fluids, resulting in an abnormal pH.

name: Abnormal circulating nitrogen compound concentration
description: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a nitrogen compound in the blood circulation.

name: Reduced consciousness
description: Abnormally diminished level of attention, responsiveness, or wakefulness.

name: Hemiplegia/hemiparesis
description: Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.

name: Intestinal pseudo-obstruction
description: A functional rather than mechanical obstruction of the intestines, associated with manifestations that resemble those caused by an intestinal obstruction, including distension, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, constipation or diarrhea, in an individual in whom a mechanical blockage has been excluded.

name: Malnutrition
description: A deficiency in the intake of energy and nutrients.

name: Cranial hyperostosis
description: Excessive growth of the bones of cranium, i.e., of the skull.

name: Elevated pulmonary artery pressure
description: An abnormally elevated blood pressure in the circulation of the pulmonary artery.

name: Supraventricular arrhythmia
description: A type of arrhythmia that originates above the ventricles, whereby the electrical impulse propagates down the normal His Purkinje system similar to normal sinus rhythm.

name: Abnormality of body weight
description: An abnormal increase or decrease of weight or an abnormal distribution of mass in the body.

name: Ocular anterior segment dysgenesis
description: Abnormal development (dysgenesis) of the anterior segment of the eye globe. These structures are mainly of mesenchymal origin.

name: Intracranial cystic lesion
description: A cystic lesion originating within the brain.

name: Ectopic calcification
description: Deposition of calcium salts in a tissue or location in which calcification does not normally occur.

name: Erythema
description: Redness of the skin, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.

name: Impaired visuospatial constructive cognition
description: Reduced ability affecting mainly visuospatial cognition which may be tested using pattern construction (for example by Differential Ability Scales, which test a person's strengths and weaknesses across a range of intellectual abilities).

name: Impaired proprioception
description: A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position.

name: Intellectual disability, severe
description: Severe mental retardation is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 20-34.

name: Abnormality of the upper urinary tract
description: An abnormality of the upper urinary tract.

name: Paraplegia/paraparesis
description: Weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities. Paraplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas paraparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.

name: Anemia of inadequate production
description: A kind of anemia characterized by inadequate production of erythrocytes.

name: Abnormal cerebral subcortex morphology
description: An abnormality of the cerebral subcortex.

name: Abnormal corpus striatum morphology
description: Abnormality of the striatum, which is the largest nucleus of the basal ganglia, comprising the caudate, putamen and ventral striatum, including the nucleus accumbens.

name: Abnormal circulating monocarboxylic acid concentration
description: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a monocarboxylic acid in the blood circulation.

name: Abnormal systemic arterial morphology
description: An abnormality of the systemic arterial tree, which consists of the aorta and other systemic arteries.

name: Abnormal blood glucose concentration
description: An abnormality of the concentration of glucose in the blood.

name: Abnormal cellular physiology
description: An abnormality in a cellular process.

name: Abnormality of immune system physiology
description: A functional abnormality of the immune system.

name: Paraplegia
description: Severe or complete weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities.

name: Weakness due to upper motor neuron dysfunction
description: Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Paralysis due to lesions of the principle motor tracts is related to a lesion in the corticospinal, corticobulbar or brainstem descending (subcorticospinal) neurons.

name: Peripheral neuropathy
description: Peripheral neuropathy is a general term for any disorder of the peripheral nervous system. The main clinical features used to classify peripheral neuropathy are distribution, type (mainly demyelinating versus mainly axonal), duration, and course.

name: Paroxysmal involuntary eye movements
description: Sudden-onset episode of abnormal, involuntary eye movements.

name: Horizontal pendular nystagmus
description: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements of equal velocity.

name: Retinal pigment epithelial mottling
description: Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium, i.e., localized or generalized fundal pigment granularity associated with processes at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium.

name: Abnormal retinal vascular morphology
description: A structural abnormality of retinal vasculature.

name: Abnormality of the vasculature of the eye
description: Abnormality of the vasculature of the eye

name: Abnormal light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram
description: An abnormality of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.

name: Bilateral sensorineural hearing impairment
description: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects both ears.

name: Renal hypoplasia/aplasia
description: Absence or underdevelopment of the kidney.

name: Floppy infant
description: Floppiness/hypotonia is defined as reduced resistance to passive movement of joints. Physical examination of floppy/hypotonic infants shows head lag, lack of shoulder and elbow muscle contraction on traction response, inability to tighten the shoulder girdle muscles (or slipping through) when held under the axillae, scarf sign (when the arm is pulled to the opposite side, the arm wraps around the neck with the elbow crossing midline), hyperdorsiflexion of the feet, easy apposition of the thumb against the forearm, feet touching the cheek with ease and without discomfort, frog leg position, and inverted U sign on ventral suspension (head, arms, and legs hanging down without elbow or knee flexion and the trunk rounded in a dome shape).

name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
description: Decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.

name: Distal lower limb muscle weakness
description: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the legs.

name: Abnormal axial skeleton morphology
description: An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum.

name: Abnormality of the musculature of the limbs
description: Abnormality of the musculature of the limbs

name: Limb pain
description: Chronic pain in the limbs with no clear focal etiology.

name: Undetectable light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram
description: Absence of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.

name: Short stature
description: A height below that which is expected according to age and gender norms. Although there is no universally accepted definition of short stature, many refer to \"short stature\" as height more than 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender (or below the 3rd percentile for age and gender dependent norms).

name: Involuntary movements
description: Involuntary contractions of muscle leading to involuntary movements of extremities, neck, trunk, or face.

name: Long-tract sign
description: Long-tract signs refer to symptoms that are attributable to the involvement of the long fiber tracts in the spinal cord, which connect the spinal cord to the brain and mediate spinal and motor functions. These include spasticity, hyperreflexia, and abnormal reflexes such as Babinski or Hoffman's sign. If possible, it is preferable to use the precise HPO terms for these abnormalities.

name: Tetraplegia
description: Paralysis of all four limbs, and trunk of the body below the level of an associated injury to the spinal cord. The etiology of quadriplegia is similar to that of paraplegia except that the lesion is in the cervical spinal cord rather than in the thoracic or lumbar segments of the spinal cord.

name: Astrocytosis
description: Proliferation of astrocytes in the area of a lesion of the central nervous system.

name: Distal muscle weakness
description: Reduced strength of the musculature of the distal extremities.

name: Language impairment
description: Language impairment is a deficit in comprehension or production of language that includes reduced vocabulary, limited sentence structure, or impairments in written or spoken communication. Language abilities are substantially and quantifiably below age expectations.

name: Abnormal corticospinal tract morphology
description: Abnormality of the corticospinal tract, which is the chief element of the pyramidal system (the principle motor tract) and is the only direct connection between the cerebrum and the spinal cord.

name: Upper motor neuron dysfunction
description: A functional anomaly of the upper motor neuron. The upper motor neurons are neurons of the primary motor cortex which project to the brainstem and spinal chord via the corticonuclear, corticobulbar and corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts. They are involved in control of voluntary movements. Dysfunction leads to weakness, impairment of fine motor movements, spasticity, hyperreflexia and abnormal pyramidal signs.

name: Poor head control
description: Difficulty to maintain correct position of the head while standing or sitting. Infant head lag is observed when the head seems to flop around or lags posteriorly behind the trunk. Several articles have maintained that head lag should be absent by age 3 to 4 months.

name: Impaired vibratory sensation
description: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to bony prominences such as the malleoli at the ankles or the metacarpal-phalangeal joints. There is a slow decay of vibration from the tuning fork. The degree of vibratory sense loss can be crudely estimated by counting the number of seconds that the examiner can perceive the vibration longer than the patient.

name: Loss of ambulation
description: Inability to walk in a person who previous had the ability to walk.

name: Cerebral calcification
description: The presence of calcium deposition within the cerebrum.

name: Abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the cerebral cortex.

name: Steatorrhea
description: Greater than normal amounts of fat in the feces. This is a result of malabsorption of lipids in the small intestine and results in frothy foul-smelling fecal matter that floats.

name: Gastrointestinal dysmotility
description: Abnormal intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis, related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.

name: Abnormal cerebral white matter morphology
description: An abnormality of the cerebral white matter.

name: Leukodystrophy
description: Leukodystrophy refers to deterioration of white matter of the brain resulting from degeneration of myelin sheaths in the CNS. Their basic defect is directly related to the synthesis and maintenance of myelin membranes. Symmetric white matter involvement at MRI is a typical finding in patients with leukodystrophies.

name: Stroke-like episode
description: No consensus exists on what a stroke-like episode is, but these episodes can be functionally defined as a new neurological deficit, occurring with or without the context of seizures, which last longer than 24 hours.

name: Cogwheel rigidity
description: A type of rigidity in which a muscle responds with cogwheellike jerks to the use of constant force in bending the limb (i.e., it gives way in little, repeated jerks when the muscle is passively stretched).

name: Gliosis
description: Gliosis is the focal proliferation of glial cells in the central nervous system.

name: Generalized-onset seizure
description: A generalized-onset seizure is a type of seizure originating at some point within, and rapidly engaging, bilaterally distributed networks. The networks may include cortical and subcortical structures but not necessarily the entire cortex.

name: Hepatomegaly
description: Abnormally increased size of the liver.

name: Abnormal intestine morphology
description: An abnormality of the intestine. The closely related term enteropathy is used to refer to any disease of the intestine.

name: Athetosis
description: A slow, continuous, involuntary writhing movement that prevents maintenance of a stable posture. Athetosis involves continuous smooth movements that appear random and are not composed of recognizable sub-movements or movement fragments. In contrast to chorea, in athetosis, the same regions of the body are repeatedly involved. Athetosis may worsen with attempts at movement of posture, but athetosis can also occur at rest.

name: Headache
description: Cephalgia, or pain sensed in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.

name: Recurrent paroxysmal headache
description: Repeated episodes of headache with rapid onset, reaching a peak within minutes and of short duration (less than one hour) with pain that is throbbing, pulsating, or bursting in quality.

name: Abnormal caudate nucleus morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the caudate nucleus.

name: Action tremor
description: A tremor present when the limbs are active, either when outstretched in a certain position or throughout a voluntary movement.

name: Leukoencephalopathy
description: This term describes abnormality of the white matter of the cerebrum resulting from damage to the myelin sheaths of nerve cells.

name: EEG abnormality
description: Abnormality observed by electroencephalogram (EEG), which is used to record of the brain's spontaneous electrical activity from multiple electrodes placed on the scalp.

name: Memory impairment
description: An impairment of memory as manifested by a reduced ability to remember things such as dates and names, and increased forgetfulness.

name: Developmental regression
description: Loss of developmental skills, as manifested by loss of developmental milestones.

name: Aphasia
description: An acquired language impairment of some or all of the abilities to produce or comprehend speech and to read or write.

name: Fat malabsorption
description: Abnormality of the absorption of fat from the gastrointestinal tract.

name: Abnormal calvaria morphology
description: Abnormality of the morphology (structure) of the calvaria (skullcap), that is, of that part of the skull that is made up of the superior portions of the frontal bone, occipital bone, and parietal bones and covers the cranial cavity that contains the brain.

name: Abnormality of the immune system
description: An abnormality of the immune system.

name: Delayed skeletal maturation
description: A decreased rate of skeletal maturation. Delayed skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.

name: 3-Methylglutaconic aciduria
description: An increased amount of 3-methylglutaconic acid in the urine.

name: Increased circulating pyruvate concentration
description: The concentration of pyruvate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

name: Exercise intolerance
description: A functional motor deficit where individuals whose responses to the challenges of exercise fail to achieve levels considered normal for their age and gender.

name: Muscle stiffness
description: A condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm.

name: Infantile onset
description: Onset of signs or symptoms of disease between 28 days to one year of life.

name: Neonatal onset
description: Onset of signs or symptoms of disease within the first 28 days of life.

name: Onset
description: The age group in which disease manifestations appear.

name: Limb muscle weakness
description: Reduced strength and weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.

name: Proximal muscle weakness
description: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles.

name: Variable expressivity
description: A variable severity of phenotypic features.

name: Typified by incomplete penetrance
description: Description of conditions in which not all individuals with a given genotype exhibit the disease. Penetrance is the proportion that develop disease given a lifespan of 80 years.

name: Abnormality of the biliary system
description: An abnormality of the biliary system.

name: Abnormal muscle fiber morphology
description: Any abnormality of the skeletal muscle cell. Muscle fibers are subdivided into two types. Type I fibers are fatigue-resistant and rich in oxidative enzymes (they stain light with the myosin ATPase reaction), and type II fibers are fast-contracting, fatigue-prone, and rich in glycolytic enzymes (these fibers stain darkly). Normal muscle tissue has a random distribution of type I and type II fibers.

name: Babinski sign
description: Upturning of the big toe (and sometimes fanning of the other toes) in response to stimulation of the sole of the foot. If the Babinski sign is present it can indicate damage to the corticospinal tract.

name: Abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract
description: An abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract.

name: Upper limb muscle weakness
description: Weakness of the muscles of the arms.

name: Somatic sensory dysfunction
description: An abnormality of the primary sensation that is mediated by peripheral nerves (pain, temperature, touch, vibration, joint position). The word hypoesthesia (or hypesthesia) refers to a reduction in cutaneous sensation to a specific type of testing.

name: Abnormal pattern of respiration
description: An anomaly of the rhythm or depth of breathing.

name: Abnormal respiratory system physiology
description: Abnormal function of the respiratory system.

name: Abnormal cerebrospinal fluid morphology
description: An abnormality of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

name: Increased CSF protein concentration
description: Increased concentration of protein in the cerebrospinal fluid.

name: Abnormality of thyroid physiology
description: An abnormal functionality of the thyroid gland.

name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the central nervous system
description: Absence or underdevelopment of tissue in the central nervous system.

name: Abnormality of the musculature
description: Abnormality originating in one or more muscles, i.e., of the set of muscles of body.

name: Abnormality of urine homeostasis
description: An abnormality of the composition of urine or the levels of its components.

name: Abnormal circulating amino acid concentration
description: The presence of an abnormal decrease or increase of one or more amino acids in the blood circulation.

name: Lactic acidosis
description: An abnormal buildup of lactic acid in the body, leading to acidification of the blood and other bodily fluids.

name: Allergic rhinitis
description: It is characterized by one or more symptoms including sneezing, itching, nasal congestion, and rhinorrhea.

name: Myopathy
description: A disorder of muscle unrelated to impairment of innervation or neuromuscular junction.

name: Visceromegaly
description: Abnormal increased size of the viscera of the abdomen.

name: Abnormal bone structure
description: Any anomaly in the composite material or the layered arrangement of the bony skeleton.

name: Muscle spasm
description: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles.

name: Peripheral axonal neuropathy
description: An abnormality characterized by disruption of the normal functioning of peripheral axons.

name: Abnormal speech pattern
description: An abnormality in the sound (volume) or cadence (rate) of speech.

name: Abnormal cardiovascular system physiology
description: Abnormal functionality of the cardiovascular system.

name: Abnormality of dental structure
description: An abnormality of the structure or composition of the teeth.

name: Cardiac conduction abnormality
description: Any anomaly of the progression of electrical impulses through the heart.

name: Abnormal ear physiology
description: Any functional anomaly of the ear.

name: Clinical course
description: The course a disease typically takes from its onset, progression in time, and eventual resolution or death of the affected individual.

name: Abnormal oral morphology
description: Any structural anomaly of the mouth, which is also known as the oral cavity.

name: Abnormal reflex
description: Any anomaly of a reflex, i.e., of an automatic response mediated by the nervous system (a reflex does not need the intervention of conscious thought to occur).

name: Abnormal superficial reflex
description: An anomaly of a reflex that is elicited as a motor response to scraping of the skin. They are generally graded as present or absent. They differ from tendon reflexes in that the sensory signal must ascend the spinal cord to reach the brain and then descend the spinal cord to reach the motor neurons.

name: Abnormal urine carboxylic acid level
description: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carboxylic acid in the urine.

name: Impairment in personality functioning
description: A maladaptive personality trait characterized by moderate or greater impairment in personality (self /interpersonal) functioning.

name: Abnormal circulating metabolite concentration
description: An abnormal level of an analyte measured in the blood.

name: Generalized-onset motor seizure
description: A generalized motor seizure is a type of generalized-onset seizure with predominantly motor (involving musculature) signs. The motor event could consist of an increase (positive) or decrease (negative) in muscle contraction to produce a movement.

name: Myoclonic seizure
description: A myoclonic seizure is a type of motor seizure characterized by sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction of muscles or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal). Myoclonus is less regularly repetitive and less sustained than is clonus.

name: Abnormal urine pH
description: A deviation of urine pH from the normal range of 4.5 to 7.8.

name: Abnormality of the musculoskeletal system
description: An anomaly of the musculoskeletal system, which consists of the bones of the skeleton, muscles, cartilage, tendons, ligaments, joints, and other connective tissue. The musculoskeletal system supports the weight of the body, maintains body position and produces movements of the body or of parts of the body.

name: Abnormal blood vessel morphology
description: Any structural anomaly of a blood vessel (artery, arteriole, capillary, venule, or vein).

name: Abnormal urine metabolite level
description: Any deviation from the normal amount of a metabolite in urine.

name: Pre-capillary pulmonary hypertension
description: Pre-capillary pulmonary hypertension is a haemodynamic condition characterized by elevated mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP over 20 mmHg) and pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR 3 Wood units or more) accompanied by normal pulmonary artery wedge pressure (PAWP not more than 15 mmHg).

name: Increased blood pressure
description: Abnormal increase in blood pressure. An individual measurement of increased blood pressure does not necessarily imply hypertension. In practical terms, multiple measurements are recommended to diagnose the presence of hypertension.

name: Abnormal renal corpuscle morphology
description: Any anomalous structure of the renal corpuscle, which is the initial component of the nephron that filters blood. The renal corpuscle consists of a knot of capillaries (glomerulus) that is surrounded by a double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.

name: Abnormal systemic blood pressure
description: A chronic deviation from normal pressure in the systemic arterial system.

name: Abnormality of cardiovascular system electrophysiology
description: An anomaly of the electrical conduction physiology of the heart.

name: Abnormal CSF metabolite concentration
description: Any deviation from the normal range of concentration of a metabolite in the cerebrospinal fluid.

name: Abnormal CSF protein concentration
description: Any deviation from the normal range of a protein concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.

name: Abnormal affect
description: An anomaly in intensity, frequency, or duration of the verbal or behavioral expression of emotions, feelings, or thoughts.

name: Abnormal volitional state
description: An abnormality of internal states of motivation or drive that compromise, or interfere with, the ability of the person to attend to basic personal, social, or vocational activities.

name: Diagnostic behavioral phenotype
description: The Human Phenotype Ontology provides terms to describe specific phenotypic abnormalities rather than disease diagnoses. Nevertheless, it is common for descriptions such as 'Autism' to be used to describe individuals affected with Mendelian forms of neurodevelopmental disease and many other conditions. If possible, we recommend annotation using specific terms in other branchs of the Atypical behavior subontology, but if this is not possible, then terms from this branch may be used.

name: Abnormality of central nervous system electrophysiology
description: Abnormality of central nervous system electrophysiology

name: Tetraplegia/tetraparesis
description: Loss of strength in all four limbs. Tetraplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas Tetraparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.

name: Abnormal visual field test
description: Abnormal result of a test designed to test an individual's central and peripheral vision by determining the ability of the individual to perceive objects at differing locations of the visual field.

name: Abnormal cardiovascular system morphology
description: Any structural anomaly of the heart and blood vessels.

name: Central nervous system cyst
description: A fluid-filled sac (cyst) located within the central nervous system.

name: Abnormal cardiac ventricular function
description: An abnormality of the cardiac ventricular function.

name: Abnormality of pulmonary circulation
description: A functional anomaly of that portion of the cardiosvascular system that carries deoxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs and returns oxygenated blood back to the heart.

name: Abnormal gastrointestinal motility
description: An anomaly of the muscular contractions that propel food though the gastrointestinal tract.

name: Thin corpus callosum
description: An abnormally thin corpus callous, due to atrophy, hypoplasia or agenesis. This term is intended to be used in situations where it is not known if thinning of the corpus callosum (for instance, as visualized by magnetic resonance tomography) is due to abnormal development (e.g. a leukodystrophy) or atrophy following normal development (e.g. neurodegeneration).

name: Abnormal spleen morphology
description: Any anomaly of the structure of the spleen.

name: Fetal anomaly
description: Structural or functional abnormalities of the fetus. Note that this section comprises terms that describe abnormalities that are specific to the fetus or differ from the corresponding general terms. A term from anywhere in the Human Phenotype Ontology can be applied to a fetus if appropriate.

name: Inheritance qualifier
description: The terms in this hierarchy can be used to specify the context in which inheritance of a disease is typically observed.

name: Abnormal emotional state
description: Emotions are complex psychological states that involve three distinct components: a subjective experience, a physiological response, and a behavioral or expressive response. In an abnormal emotional state, an affected individual shows altered intensity, frequency, or duration of emotional experiences.

name: Abnormal liver morphology
description: Any structural anomaly of the bile-secreting organ that is important for detoxification, for fat, carbohydrate, and protein metabolism, and for glycogen storage.

name: Brain imaging abnormality
description: An anomaly of metabolism or structure of the brain identified by imaging.

name: Pediatric onset
description: Onset of disease manifestations before adulthood, defined here as before the age of 16 years, but excluding neonatal or congenital onset.

name: Intracranial calcification
description: Intracranial calcifications refer to calcifications within the brain parenchyma or vasculature. The five major components of the brain comprise the cerebrum, cerebellum, brain stem, pituitary gland, and hypothalamus.

name: Abnormal circulating organic compound concentration
description: Any deviation of the concentration of an orrganic compound from the normal range. An organic compound is defined as any compound that contains a carbon atom.

name: Abnormal language feature
description: The presence of any atypical form of expressive language.

name: Hyperostosis
description: Excessive growth or abnormal thickening of bone tissue.

name: Reduced attention regulation
description: An abnormality in one's ability to control their attention towards a specific subject or task can include difficulties in changing or maintaining attention.

name: Abnormal judgment
description: Beliefs that deviate from what is considered rational or within the range of normal human judgment and belief formation.

name: Abnormal experience of reality
description: Subjective phenomena or perceptions that deviate from what is considered correct or are outside the range of normal human experiences.

name: Abnormal psychotic pattern
description: Any abnormal pattern of psychotic experiences, where an individual has significant disturbances in their thoughts, perceptions, emotions, and behavior, resulting in a loss of touch with reality.

name: Mitochondrial complex I assembly model OXPHOS system
description: Mitochondrial complex I assembly model OXPHOS system

name: Maladaptive fear-related cognitions
description: Threat-based cognitive biases result in a skewed perception, experience, or processing of internal or external stimuli.

name: Abnormality of the lymphatic system
description: An anomaly of the lymphatic system, a network of lymphatic vessels that carry a clear fluid called lymph unidirectionally towards either the right lymphatic duct or the thoracic duct, which in turn drain into the right and left subclavian veins respectively.

name: Abnormal glial cell morphology
description: An abnormality of the glia cell.

name: Mendelian inheritance
description: A mode of inheritance of diseases whose pathophysiology can be traced back to deleterious variants in a single gene. The inheritance patterns of these single-gene (monogenic) diseases are often referred to as Mendelian in honor of Gregor Mendel.

name: Appendicular spasticity
description: A type of spasticity that affects one or more limbs (arms or legs).

name: Abnormal communication
description: Presence of any form of communication (e.g., verbal or non-verbal) that does not align with cultural expectations or developmental level.

name: Abnormal eye contact
description: Any abnormality of eye contact behavior. We define eye contact as a form of nonverbal communication between two individuals who are facing each other in which an individual directs the eyes towards the eyes or face of the other individual. Eye contact occurs frequently and voluntarily during face-to-face verbal communication. The duration and frequency of eye contact that is interpreted to be appropriate may follow social and situational norms.

name: Abnormal enzyme concentration or activity
description: Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal.

name: Decreased head circumference
description: An abnormally reduced head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart. Microcephaly is defined as a head circumference (HC) that is great than two standard deviations below the mean of age- and gender-matched population based samples. Severe microcephaly is defined with an HC that is three standard deviations below the mean.

name: Abnormality of movement
description: An abnormality of movement with a neurological basis characterized by changes in coordination and speed of voluntary movements.

name: Immunologic hypersensitivity
description: Immunological states where the immune system produces harmful responses upon reexposure to sensitizing antigens.

name: Cognitive impairment
description: Abnormal cognition is characterized by deficits in thinking, reasoning, or remembering.

name: Abnormal forebrain morphology
description: An abnormality of the forebrain, which has as its parts the telencephalon, diencephalon, lateral ventricles and third ventricle.

name: Type I diabetes mellitus
description: A chronic condition in which the pancreas produces little or no insulin. Type I diabetes mellitus is manifested by the sudden onset of severe hyperglycemia with rapid progression to diabetic ketoacidosis unless treated with insulin.

name: Abnormal cerebral vascular morphology
description: An anomaly of the cerebral blood vessels.

name: Dyskinesia
description: A movement disorder which consists of effects including diminished voluntary movements and the presence of involuntary movements.

name: Cerebral visual impairment
description: A form of loss of vision caused by damage to the visual cortex rather than a defect in the eye.

name: Abnormal fetal physiology
description: Any functional anomaly of the fetus.

name: Abnormal cellular phenotype
description: An anomaly of cellular morphology or physiology.

name: Abnormal esophagus physiology
description: Any physiological abnormality of the esophagus.

name: Stuttering
description: Disruptions in the production of speech sounds, with involuntary repetitions of words or parts of words, prolongations of speech sounds, or complete blockage of speech production for several seconds.

name: Abnormal skeletal muscle morphology
description: A structural abnormality of a skeletal muscle.

name: Abnormal skeletal morphology
description: An abnormality of the form, structure, or size of the skeletal system.

name: Abnormal musculoskeletal physiology
description: An abnormality of the function of the skeletal system.

name: Abnormal bone ossification
description: Any anomaly in the formation of bone or of a bony substance, or the conversion of fibrous tissue or of cartilage into bone or a bony substance.

name: Abnormal activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
description: An increased or decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.

name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex I
description: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex I, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

name: Feeding difficulties
description: Impaired ability to eat related to problems gathering food and getting ready to suck, chew, or swallow it.

name: Abnormal muscle physiology
description: A functional abnormality of a skeletal muscle.

name: Pendular nystagmus
description: Rhythmic, involuntary sinusoidal oscillations of one or both eyes. The waveform of pendular nystagmus may occur in any direction.

name: Abnormality of pancreas physiology
description: An anomaly of the function of the pancreas.

name: Abnormality of exocrine pancreas physiology
description: A functional anomaly of the acinar gland portion of the pancreas that secretes digestive enzymes.

name: Abnormality of the mitochondrion
description: An anomaly of the mitochondrion, the membranous cytoplasmic organelle the interior of which is subdivided by cristae. The mitochondrion is a self replicating organelle that is the site of tissue respiration.

name: Abnormal renal morphology
description: Any structural anomaly of the kidney.

name: Abnormal renal physiology
description: An abnormal functionality of the kidney.

name: Abnormal homeostasis
description: An anomaly in the processes involved in the maintenance of an internal equilibrium.

name: Abnormal eye morphology
description: A structural anomaly of the globe of the eye, or bulbus oculi.

name: Aciduria
description: Excretion of urine with an acid pH, i.e., having an increased hydrogen ion concentration.

name: Abnormality of the parathyroid physiology
description: A functional abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

name: Arrhythmia
description: Any cardiac rhythm other than the normal sinus rhythm. Such a rhythm may be either of sinus or ectopic origin and either regular or irregular. An arrhythmia may be due to a disturbance in impulse formation or conduction or both.

name: Abdominal symptom
description: A subjective manifestation of disease localized to the abdomen.

name: Epileptic spasm
description: A sudden flexion, extension, or mixed extension-flexion of predominantly proximal and truncal muscles that is usually more sustained than a myoclonic movement but not as sustained as a tonic seizure. Limited forms may occur: Grimacing, head nodding, or subtle eye movements. Epileptic spasms frequently occur in clusters. Infantile spasms are the best known form, but spasms can occur at all ages

name: Abnormal skin morphology
description: Any morphological abnormality of the skin.

name: Abnormality of skin physiology
description: Any abnormality of the physiological function of the skin.

name: Inflammatory abnormality of the skin
description: The presence of inflammation of the skin. That is, an abnormality of the skin resulting from the local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes.

name: Abnormal skin adnexa morphology
description: An abnormality of the skin adnexa (skin appendages), which are specialized skin structures located within the dermis and focally within the subcutaneous fatty tissue, comprising three histologically distinct structures: (1) the pilosebaceous unit (hair follicle and sebaceous glands); (2) the eccrine sweat glands; and (3) the apocrine glands.

name: Abnormality of the urinary system physiology
description: Abnormality of the urinary system physiology

name: Abnormal hindbrain morphology
description: An abnormality of the hindbrain, also known as the rhombencephalon.

name: Abnormal metencephalon morphology
description: An abnormality of the metencephalon. The metencephalon is the part of the hindbrain that consists of the pons and the cerebellum.

name: Severe global developmental delay
description: A severe delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

name: Generalized abnormality of skin
description: An abnormality of the skin that is not localized to any one particular region.

name: Functional abnormality of the inner ear
description: An abnormality of the function of the inner ear.

name: Abnormal CNS myelination
description: An abnormality of myelination of nerves in the central nervous system.

name: Abnormal central motor function
description: An anomaly of the control or production of movement in the central nervous system.

name: Abnormal eye physiology
description: A functional anomaly of the eye.

name: Hemianopia
description: Partial or complete loss of vision in one half of the visual field of one or both eyes.

name: Abnormal circulating enzyme concentration or activity
description: Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal in the blood circulation.

name: Rhinitis
description: Inflammation of the nasal mucosa with nasal congestion.

name: Abnormal brainstem MRI signal intensity
description: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem.

name: Focal T2 hyperintense brainstem lesion
description: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.

name: Neurodevelopmental delay
description: Neurodevelopmental delay (NDD) refers to delays in the maturation of the brain and central nervous system; infants and young children with NDD may experience delays in the development of one or more skills including gross motor abilities, fine-motor coordination, language abilities and ability to solve increasingly complex problems.

name: Neurodevelopmental abnormality
description: A deviation from normal of the neurological development of a child, which may include any or all of the aspects of the development of personal, social, gross or fine motor, and cognitive abilities.

name: Widened cerebral subarachnoid space
description: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebrum.

name: Abnormal optic disc morphology
description: A morphological abnormality of the optic disc, i.e., of the portion of the optic nerve clinically visible on fundoscopic examination.

name: Clinical modifier
description: This subontology is designed to provide terms to characterize and specify the phenotypic abnormalities defined in the Phenotypic abnormality subontology, with respect to severity, laterality, age of onset, and other aspects.

name: Abnormal urine protein level
description: Any deviation of the concentration of one or more proteins in the urine.

name: Motor seizure
description: A motor seizure is a type of seizure that is characterized at onset by involvement of the skeletal musculature. The motor event could consist of an increase (positive) or decrease (negative) in muscle contraction to produce a movement.

name: Abnormality of digestive system physiology
description: A functional anomaly of the digestive system.

name: Abnormal digestive system morphology
description: A structural anomaly of the digestive system.

name: Abnormal brain lactate level by MRS
description: A deviation from normal of the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

name: Fetal distress
description: An intrauterine state characterized by suboptimal values in the fetal heart rate, oxygenation of fetal blood, or other parameters indicative of compromise of the fetus. Signs of fetal distress include repetitive variable decelerations, fetal tachycardia or bradycardia, late decelerations, or low biophysical profile.

name: Constitutional symptom
description: A symptom or manifestation indicating a systemic or general effect of a disease and that may affect the general well-being or status of an individual.

name: Abnormal hepatobiliary system physiology
description: A functional anomaly of the hepatobiliary system

name: Functional abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract
description: Abnormal functionality of the gastrointestinal tract.

name: Abnormal renal cortex morphology
description: An abnormality of the cortex of the kidney.

name: Abnormal gastrointestinal tract morphology
description: Abnormal structure of the gastrointestinal tract.

name: Abnormal metabolic brain imaging by MRS
description: An anomaly of metabolism in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

name: Allergy
description: An allergy is an immune response or reaction to substances that are usually not harmful.

name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cerebral white matter
description: Absence or underdevelopment of the cerebral white matter.

name: Abnormal brain morphology
description: A structural abnormality of the brain, which has as its parts the forebrain, midbrain, and hindbrain.

name: Brain atrophy
description: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of brain tissue that was once present.

name: Abnormal myelination
description: Any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons.

name: Infantile spasms
description: Infantile spasms represent a subset of \"epileptic spasms\". Infantile Spasms are epileptic spasms starting in the first year of life (infancy).

name: Lower limb pain
description: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the leg.

name: Pain
description: An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with actual or potential tissue damage, or described in terms of such damage.

name: Abnormal involuntary eye movements
description: Anomalous movements of the eyes that occur without the subject wanting them to happen.

name: Abnormal nephron morphology
description: A structural anomaly of the nephron.

name: Abnormal nervous system physiology
description: A functional anomaly of the nervous system.

name: Abnormal nervous system morphology
description: A structural anomaly of the nervous system.

name: Abnormal inflammatory response
description: Any anomaly of the inflammatory response, a response to injury or infection characterized by local vasodilation, extravasation of plasma into intercellular spaces and accumulation of white blood cells and macrophages.

name: Increased inflammatory response
description: A abnormal increase in the inflammatory response to injury or infection.

name: Small basal ganglia
description: Decreased size of the basal ganglia.

name: Abnormal subarachnoid space morphology
description: Abnormality in the space in the meninges beneath the arachnoid membrane and above the pia mater that contains the cerebrospinal fluid.

name: Widened subarachnoid space
description: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater.

name: Elevated brain lactate level by MRS
description: An increase in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

name: Impaired vibration sensation in the lower limbs
description: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the legs.

name: Increased circulating lactate concentration
description: Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35).

name: Abnormality of body height
description: Deviation from the norm of height with respect to that which is expected according to age and gender norms.

name: Mode of inheritance
description: The pattern in which a particular genetic trait or disorder is passed from one generation to the next.

name: Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism
description: Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is characterized by reduced function of the gonads (testes in males or ovaries in females) and results from the absence of the gonadal stimulating pituitary hormones: follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).

name: Microcephaly
description: Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender.

name: Hearing abnormality
description: An abnormality of the sensory perception of sound.

name: Hearing impairment
description: A decreased magnitude of the sensory perception of sound.

name: Sensorineural hearing impairment
description: A type of hearing impairment in one or both ears related to an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve.

name: Progressive sensorineural hearing impairment
description: A progressive form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

name: Abnormality of skull size
description: Any abnormality of the size of the skull.

name: Abnormality of the eye
description: Any abnormality of the eye, including location, spacing, and intraocular abnormalities.

name: Strabismus
description: A misalignment of the eyes so that the visual axes deviate from bifoveal fixation. The classification of strabismus may be based on a number of features including the relative position of the eyes, whether the deviation is latent or manifest, intermittent or constant, concomitant or otherwise and according to the age of onset and the relevance of any associated refractive error.

name: Retinopathy
description: Any noninflammatory disease of the retina. This nonspecific term is retained here because of its wide use in the literature, but if possible new annotations should indicate the precise type of retinal abnormality.

name: Abnormality of eye movement
description: An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eye movements or their control.

name: Visual impairment
description: Visual impairment (or vision impairment) is vision loss (of a person) to such a degree as to qualify as an additional support need through a significant limitation of visual capability resulting from either disease, trauma, or congenital or degenerative conditions that cannot be corrected by conventional means, such as refractive correction, medication, or surgery.

name: Ptosis
description: The upper eyelid margin is positioned 3 mm or more lower than usual and covers the superior portion of the iris (objective); or, the upper lid margin obscures at least part of the pupil (subjective).

name: Rod-cone dystrophy
description: An inherited retinal disease subtype in which the rod photoreceptors appear to be more severely affected than the cone photoreceptors. Typical presentation is with nyctalopia (due to rod dysfunction) followed by loss of mid-peripheral field of vision, which gradually extends and leaves many patients with a small central island of vision due to the preservation of macular cones.

name: Abnormal retinal morphology
description: A structural abnormality of the retina.

name: Abnormal oral cavity morphology
description: Abnormality of the oral cavity, i.e., the opening or hollow part of the mouth.

name: Abnormality of the genital system
description: An abnormality of the genital system.

name: Abnormality of the urinary system
description: An abnormality of the urinary system.

name: Abnormality of reproductive system physiology
description: An abnormal functionality of the genital system.

name: Proteinuria
description: Increased levels of protein in the urine.

name: Abnormal renal glomerulus morphology
description: A structural anomaly of the glomerulus.

name: Glomerular sclerosis
description: Accumulation of scar tissue within the glomerulus.

name: Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis
description: Segmental accumulation of scar tissue in individual (but not all) glomeruli.

name: Nephropathy
description: A nonspecific term referring to disease or damage of the kidneys.

name: Proximal tubulopathy
description: Dysfunction of the proximal tubule, which is the portion of the duct system of the nephron of the kidney which leads from Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle.

name: Abnormality of the genitourinary system
description: The presence of any abnormality of the genitourinary system.

name: Renal tubular dysfunction
description: Abnormal function of the renal tubule. The basic functional unit of the kidney, the nephron, consists of a renal corpuscle attached to a renal tubule, with roughly 0.8 to 1.5 nephrons per adult kidney. The functions of the renal tubule include reabsorption of water, electrolytes, glucose, and amino acids and secretion of substances such as uric acid.

name: Hypogonadism
description: A decreased functionality of the gonad.

name: Abnormality of head or neck
description: An abnormality of head and neck.

name: Autosomal recessive inheritance
description: A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in individuals with two pathogenic alleles, either homozygotes (two copies of the same mutant allele) or compound heterozygotes (whereby each copy of a gene has a distinct mutant allele).

name: Abnormal electroretinogram
description: Any abnormality of the electrical responses of various cell types in the retina as measured by electroretinography.

name: Azotemia
description: An increased concentration of nitrogen compounds in the blood.

name: Developmental cataract
description: A cataract that occurs congenitally as the result of a developmental defect, in contrast to the majority of cataracts that occur in adulthood as the result of degenerative changes of the lens.

name: Congestive heart failure
description: The presence of an abnormality of cardiac function that is responsible for the failure of the heart to pump blood at a rate that is commensurate with the needs of the tissues or a state in which abnormally elevated filling pressures are required for the heart to do so. Heart failure is frequently related to a defect in myocardial contraction.

name: Abnormal myocardium morphology
description: A structural anomaly of the muscle layer of the heart wall.

name: Cardiomyopathy
description: A myocardial disorder in which the heart muscle is structurally and functionally abnormal, in the absence of coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular disease and congenital heart disease sufficient to cause the observed myocardial abnormality.

name: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
description: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is defined by the presence of increased ventricular wall thickness or mass in the absence of loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) sufficient to cause the observed abnormality.

name: Dilated cardiomyopathy
description: Dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) is defined by the presence of left ventricular dilatation and left ventricular systolic dysfunction in the absence of abnormal loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) or coronary artery disease sufficient to cause global systolic impairment. Right ventricular dilation and dysfunction may be present but are not necessary for the diagnosis.

name: Abnormal left ventricle morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the left ventricle of the heart.

name: Left ventricular hypertrophy
description: Enlargement or increased size of the heart left ventricle.

name: Abnormal heart morphology
description: Any structural anomaly of the heart.

name: Abnormal cardiac ventricle morphology
description: An abnormality of a cardiac ventricle.

name: Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome
description: A disorder of the cardiac conduction system of the heart characterized by ventricular preexcitation due to the presence of an abnormal accessory atrioventricular electrical conduction pathway.

name: Progressive hearing impairment
description: A progressive form of hearing impairment.

name: Pancreatitis
description: The presence of inflammation in the pancreas.

name: Exocrine pancreatic insufficiency
description: Impaired function of the exocrine pancreas associated with a reduced ability to digest foods because of lack of digestive enzymes.

name: Splenomegaly
description: Abnormal increased size of the spleen.

name: Ventricular hypertrophy
description: Enlargement of the cardiac ventricular muscle tissue with increase in the width of the wall of the ventricle and loss of elasticity. Ventricular hypertrophy is clinically differentiated into left and right ventricular hypertrophy.

name: Abnormality of the cardiovascular system
description: Any abnormality of the cardiovascular system.

name: Abnormality of the integument
description: An abnormality of the integument, which consists of the skin and the superficial fascia.

name: Specific learning disability
description: Impairment of certain skills such as reading or writing, coordination, self-control, or attention that interfere with the ability to learn. The impairment is not related to a global deficiency of intelligence.

name: Dystonia
description: An abnormally increased muscular tone that causes fixed abnormal postures. There is a slow, intermittent twisting motion that leads to exaggerated turning and posture of the extremities and trunk.

name: Myoclonus
description: Very brief, involuntary random muscular contractions occurring at rest, in response to sensory stimuli, or accompanying voluntary movements.

name: Tremor
description: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement about a joint axis.

name: Psychotic mentation
description: A pattern of thinking and perceiving characterized by a loss of contact with reality, leading to significant changes in thoughts, perceptions, and behaviors.

name: Hyperreflexia
description: Hyperreflexia is the presence of hyperactive stretch reflexes of the muscles.

name: Cholestasis
description: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts.

name: Decreased liver function
description: Reduced ability of the liver to perform its functions.

name: Abnormality of the musculature of the lower limbs
description: Abnormality of the musculature of the lower limbs

name: Abnormal abdomen morphology
description: A structural abnormality of the abdomen ('belly'), that is, the part of the body between the pelvis and the thorax.

name: Failure to thrive
description: Failure to thrive (FTT) refers to a child whose physical growth is substantially below the norm.

name: Growth delay
description: A deficiency or slowing down of growth pre- and postnatally.

name: Intrauterine growth retardation
description: An abnormal restriction of fetal growth with fetal weight below the tenth percentile for gestational age.

name: Abnormality of blood and blood-forming tissues
description: An abnormality of the hematopoietic system.

name: Abnormal cerebellum morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the cerebellum.

name: Abnormal erythrocyte morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of erythrocytes (red-blood cells).

name: Chorea
description: Chorea (Greek for 'dance') refers to widespread arrhythmic involuntary movements of a forcible, jerky and restless fashion. It is a random-appearing sequence of one or more discrete involuntary movements or movement fragments. Movements appear random because of variability in timing, duration or location. Each movement may have a distinct start and end. However, movements may be strung together and thus may appear to flow randomly from one muscle group to another. Chorea can involve the trunk, neck, face, tongue, and extremities.

name: Migraine
description: Migraine is a chronic neurological disorder characterized by episodic attacks of headache and associated symptoms.

name: Abnormality of the respiratory system
description: An abnormality of the respiratory system, which include the airways, lungs, and the respiratory muscles.

name: Pulmonary arterial hypertension
description: Pulmonary hypertension is defined mean pulmonary artery pressure of 25mmHg or more and pulmonary capillary wedge pressure of 15mmHg or less when measured by right heart catheterisation at rest and in a supine position.

name: Dyspnea
description: Difficult or labored breathing. Dyspnea is a subjective feeling only the patient can rate, e.g., on a Borg scale.

name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure
description: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure is a seizure defined by a tonic (bilateral increased tone, lasting seconds to minutes) and then a clonic (bilateral sustained rhythmic jerking) phase.

name: Respiratory distress
description: Respiratory distress is objectively observable as the physical or emotional consequences from the experience of dyspnea. The physical presentation of respiratory distress is generally referred to as labored breathing, while the sensation of respiratory distress is called shortness of breath or dyspnea.

name: Apnea
description: Lack of breathing with no movement of the respiratory muscles and no exchange of air in the lungs. This term refers to a disposition to have recurrent episodes of apnea rather than to a single event.

name: Abnormal cerebral ventricle morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the cerebral ventricles.

name: Ventriculomegaly
description: An increase in size of the ventricular system of the brain.

name: Cerebral cortical atrophy
description: Atrophy of the cortex of the cerebrum.

name: Generalized myoclonic seizure
description: A generalized myoclonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterized by bilateral, sudden, brief (<100 ms) involuntary single or multiple contraction of muscles or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal). Myoclonus is less regularly repetitive and less sustained than is clonus.

name: Basal ganglia calcification
description: The presence of calcium deposition affecting one or more structures of the basal ganglia.

name: Asthma
description: Asthma is characterized by increased responsiveness of the tracheobronchial tree to multiple stimuli, leading to narrowing of the air passages with resultant dyspnea, cough, and wheezing.

name: Gait ataxia
description: A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to coordinate the movements required for normal walking. Gait ataxia is characteirzed by a wide-based staggering gait with a tendency to fall.

name: Rigidity
description: Continuous involuntary sustained muscle contraction. When an affected muscle is passively stretched, the degree of resistance remains constant regardless of the rate at which the muscle is stretched. This feature helps to distinguish rigidity from muscle spasticity.

name: Abnormal pyramidal tract morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the pyramidal tract, whose chief element, the corticospinal tract, is the only direct connection between the brain and the spinal cord. In addition to the corticospinal tract, the pyramidal system includes the corticobulbar, corticomesencephalic, and corticopontine tracts.

name: Acidosis
description: Abnormal acid accumulation or depletion of base.

name: Hypoglycemia
description: A decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.

name: Fever
description: Body temperature elevated above the normal range.

name: Glucose intolerance
description: Glucose intolerance (GI) can be defined as dysglycemia that comprises both prediabetes and diabetes. It includes the conditions of impaired fasting glucose (IFG) and impaired glucose tolerance (IGT) and diabetes mellitus (DM).

name: Hyperammonemia
description: An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood.

name: Morphological central nervous system abnormality
description: A structural abnormality of the central nervous system.

name: Abnormality of the abdominal organs
description: An abnormality of the viscera of the abdomen.

name: Vomiting
description: Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth by means of a series of involuntary spasmic contractions.

name: Diarrhea
description: Abnormally increased frequency (usually defined as three or more) loose or watery bowel movements a day.

name: Nausea and vomiting
description: Nausea is a commonly encountered symptom that has been defined as an unpleasant painless subjective feeling that one will imminently vomit. Vomiting has been defined as the forceful expulsion of the contents of the stomach, duodenum, or jejunum through the oral cavity. While nausea and vomiting are often thought to exist on a temporal continuum, this is not always the case. There are situations when severe nausea may be present without emesis and less frequently, when emesis may be present without preceding nausea.

name: Constipation
description: Infrequent or difficult evacuation of feces.

name: Gastroesophageal reflux
description: A condition in which the stomach contents leak backwards from the stomach into the esophagus through the lower esophageal sphincter.

name: Malabsorption
description: Impaired ability to absorb one or more nutrients from the intestine.

name: Cerebral atrophy
description: Atrophy (wasting, decrease in size of cells or tissue) affecting the cerebrum.

name: Abnormal cerebral morphology
description: Any structural abnormality of the telencephalon, which is also known as the cerebrum.

name: Lower limb spasticity
description: Spasticity (velocity-dependent increase in tonic stretch reflexes with increased muscle tone and hyperexcitable tendon reflexes) in the muscles of the lower limbs, hips, and pelvis.

name: Anemia
description: A reduction in erythrocytes volume or hemoglobin concentration.

name: Reduced tendon reflexes
description: Diminution of tendon reflexes, which is an invariable sign of peripheral nerve disease.

name: Abnormal nervous system electrophysiology
description: An abnormality of the function of the electrical signals with which nerve cells communicate with each other or with muscles as measured by electrophysiological investigations.

name: Encephalopathy
description: Encephalopathy is a term that means brain disease, damage, or malfunction. In general, encephalopathy is manifested by an altered mental state.

name: Depression
description: Frequently experiencing feelings of being down, miserable, and/or hopeless; struggling to recover from these moods; having a pessimistic outlook on the future; feeling a pervasive sense of shame; having a low self-worth; experiencing thoughts of suicide and engaging in suicidal behavior.

name: Dementia
description: A loss of global cognitive ability of sufficient amount to interfere with normal social or occupational function. Dementia represents a loss of previously present cognitive abilities, generally in adults, and can affect memory, thinking, language, judgment, and behavior.

name: Short attention span
description: Reduced attention span characterized by distractibility and impulsivity.

name: Irritability
description: A proneness to anger, i.e., a tendency to become easily bothered or annoyed.

name: Anxiety
description: Intense feelings of nervousness, tension, or panic often arise in response to interpersonal stresses. There is worry about the negative effects of past unpleasant experiences and future negative possibilities. Individuals may feel fearful, apprehensive, or threatened by uncertainty, and they may also have fears of falling apart or losing control.

name: Abnormal diminished volition
description: A reduction in willful and motivated goal-directed behavior that is considered the determinant of behavior and adaptation that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action.

name: Delayed speech and language development
description: A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age.

name: Psychosis
description: A condition characterized by changes in personality and thought patterns, often accompanied by hallucinations and delusional beliefs, is known as psychosis.

name: Personality changes
description: An abnormal shift in patterns of thinking, acting, or feeling.

name: Abnormal peripheral nervous system morphology
description: A structural abnormality of the peripheral nervous system, which is composed of the nerves that lead to or branch off from the central nervous system. This includes the cranial nerves (olfactory and optic nerves are technically part of the central nervous system).

name: Reduced eye contact
description: A reduced frequency or duration of eye contact.

name: Abnormality of the endocrine system
description: An abnormality of the endocrine system.

name: Diabetes mellitus
description: A group of abnormalities characterized by hyperglycemia and glucose intolerance.

name: Abnormality of the thyroid gland
description: An abnormality of the thyroid gland.

name: Abnormal nonverbal communicative behavior
description: Abnormalities in eye contact, communicative facial expressions, gesture use, or the use of others' bodies to communicate convey shared meanings within a culture that replace or supplement verbal communication.

name: Atypical behavior
description: Atypical behavior is an abnormality in a person's actions that can be controlled or modulated by the will of the individual. While abnormal behaviors can be difficult to control, they are distinct from other abnormal actions that cannot be affected by the individual's will.

name: Abnormality of the nervous system
description: An abnormality of the nervous system.

name: Carious teeth
description: Caries is a multifactorial bacterial infection affecting the structure of the tooth. This term has been used to describe the presence of more than expected dental caries.

name: Progressive visual loss
description: A reduction of previously attained ability to see.

name: Optic disc pallor
description: A pale yellow discoloration of the optic disc (the area of the optic nerve head in the retina). The optic disc normally has a pinkish hue with a central yellowish depression.

name: External ophthalmoplegia
description: Paralysis of the external ocular muscles.

name: Abnormal conjugate eye movement
description: Any deviation from the normal motor coordination of the eyes that allows for bilateral fixation on a single object.

name: Color vision defect
description: An anomaly in the ability to discriminate between or recognize colors.

name: Retinal dystrophy
description: Retinal dystrophy is an abnormality of the retina associated with a hereditary process. Retinal dystrophies are defined by their predominantly monogenic inheritance and they are frequently associated with loss or dysfunction of photoreceptor cells as a primary or secondary event.

name: Visual loss
description: Loss of visual acuity (implying that vision was better at a certain time point in life). Otherwise the term reduced visual acuity should be used (or a subclass of that).

name: Pigmentary retinopathy
description: An abnormality of the retina characterized by pigment deposition. It is typically associated with migration and proliferation of macrophages or retinal pigment epithelial cells into the retina; melanin from these cells causes the pigmentary changes. Pigmentary retinopathy is a common final pathway of many retinal conditions and is often associated with visual loss.

name: Progressive external ophthalmoplegia
description: Initial bilateral ptosis followed by limitation of eye movements in all directions and slowing of saccades.

name: Ophthalmoparesis
description: Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement.

name: Ophthalmoplegia
description: Paralysis of one or more extraocular muscles that are responsible for eye movements.

name: Blindness
description: Blindness is the condition of lacking visual perception defined as a profound reduction in visual perception. On the 6m visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 3/60. On the 20ft visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 20/400. On the decimal visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 0.05. Blindness is typically characterized by a visual field of no greater than 10 degrees in radius around central fixation.

name: Nystagmus
description: Rhythmic, involuntary oscillations of one or both eyes related to abnormality in fixation, conjugate gaze, or vestibular mechanisms.

name: Optic atrophy
description: Atrophy of the optic nerve. Optic atrophy results from the death of the retinal ganglion cell axons that comprise the optic nerve and manifesting as a pale optic nerve on fundoscopy.

name: Horizontal nystagmus
description: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements.

name: Hypertension
description: The presence of chronic increased pressure in the systemic arterial system.

name: Abnormality of the parathyroid gland
description: An abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

name: Hypoparathyroidism
description: A condition caused by a deficiency of parathyroid hormone characterized by hypocalcemia and hyperphosphatemia.

name: Abnormality of the skeletal system
description: An abnormality of the skeletal system.

name: Intellectual disability, mild
description: Mild intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 50-69.

name: Spasticity
description: A motor disorder characterized by a velocity-dependent increase in tonic stretch reflexes with increased muscle tone, exaggerated (hyperexcitable) tendon reflexes.

name: Spastic paraplegia
description: Complete loss of the ability to move the lower limbs accompanied by spasticity of the lower limbs.

name: Dysarthria
description: Dysarthric speech is a general description referring to a neurological speech disorder characterized by poor articulation. Depending on the involved neurological structures, dysarthria may be further classified as spastic, flaccid, ataxic, hyperkinetic and hypokinetic, or mixed.

name: Global developmental delay
description: A delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child, including motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and emotional skills. This term should only be used to describe children younger than five years of age.

name: Hyporeflexia
description: Reduction of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.

name: Choreoathetosis
description: Involuntary movements characterized by both athetosis (inability to sustain muscles in a fixed position) and chorea (widespread jerky arrhythmic movements).

name: Mental deterioration
description: Loss of previously present mental abilities, generally in adults.

name: Hemiparesis
description: Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.

name: Motor delay
description: A type of Developmental delay characterized by a delay in acquiring motor skills.

name: Cerebellar atrophy
description: Cerebellar atrophy is defined as a cerebellum with initially normal structures, in a posterior fossa with normal size, which displays enlarged fissures (interfolial spaces) in comparison to the foliae secondary to loss of tissue. Cerebellar atrophy implies irreversible loss of tissue and result from an ongoing progressive disease until a final stage is reached or a single injury, e.g. an intoxication or infectious event.

name: Agenesis of corpus callosum
